    captionsSrc:
      "./assets/captions/standalone/belal-assaad/story-of-the-three-trapped-men.vtt",
    description:
      "An in-depth lesson on the famous hadith of three men trapped in a cave who were saved by calling on Allah through their most sincere secret deeds — a study of ikhlas (sincerity of the heart), goodness to parents, guarding against forbidden desire, and honesty in wealth and business.",
    takeaways: [
      "**Sincerity is the boat that saves you**: No deed is accepted or weighed by Allah unless the heart is truly sincere and honest. Even ordinary daily acts become worship when done for Allah's sake — and Iblis himself admitted he has no power over Allah's sincere, honest servants.",
      "**Do your best deeds in secret**: The three men were each saved by a private good deed no one else knew about. An act done sincerely between you and Allah alone is the most powerful kind, and you may call on such deeds when you make dua in hardship.",
      "**The first man — goodness to parents**: He always gave his elderly parents their milk before his own crying children, and one night stood waiting for them to wake rather than disturb them. Dutifulness (birr) to parents is the opposite of arrogance; disagree with respect, never with contempt, and know that a mother is owed extra care for pregnancy, birth, and nursing.",
      "**The second man — fleeing forbidden desire**: Given the chance to sin with a woman he was obsessed with, he stopped the moment she said \"fear Allah.\" Turning away from a temptation you are able to act on becomes an act of worship — and don't engineer temptations just to \"pass\" them; that plan is itself from Shaytan.",
      "**The third man — honesty in wealth**: He returned a worker's forgotten wage in full, having grown it into whole herds through honest investment. Believers keep their agreements and contracts; lying, hiding faults, or deceiving in trade strips wealth of all its blessing.",
      "**Your company shapes your fate**: All three were righteous friends who reminded one another of Allah — had even one lacked good deeds, they would all have stayed trapped. Good company is like a perfume seller and bad company like a blacksmith's furnace; choose the friends who bring you closer to Allah.",
    ],
    recap: `This lecture by Sheikh Belal Assaad is built around the famous hadith of the three men trapped in a cave, found in Bukhari and Muslim. Its overarching theme is ikhlas — the absolute sincerity and honesty of the heart — without which, the speaker stresses, no deed carries any weight with Allah. He opens by noting that any ordinary act, from moving aside for an ant colony to eating with bismillah to resisting a sin, becomes worship when it is done sincerely for Allah's sake.

To frame sincerity, he recalls the exchange in which Iblis, out of arrogance and envy, vows to lead the children of Adam astray by beautifying the material world to them — yet concedes he has no power over Allah's sincere, devoted servants. Allah affirms that this sincere path is His straight path. Sincerity, the speaker says, is tested whenever Allah commands something that clashes with our desires: do we still submit because Allah said it, or do we rebel like Iblis? He illustrates true sincerity through Ibrahim (as), who answered his father's threats with a promise to seek forgiveness for him; through Yusuf (as), who fled temptation and preferred prison to sin; and through Dawud and Sulayman (as), who held the largest kingdoms yet dealt with people in justice and generosity.

He then narrates the hadith itself. Three travelers shelter in a cave for the night, and a boulder from a landslide seals them inside with no escape. Realizing they will die, each resolves to call on Allah using a secret good deed done purely for His sake. The first recalls how he always served milk to his elderly parents before his own children, and one night stood holding the milk, refusing to wake them and refusing to feed his crying children first, until they woke — the rock shifts slightly. The second recalls a woman he was obsessed with who, in her desperation, finally submitted to him, but who stopped him with the words "fear Allah"; he walked away for Allah's sake and left her the money freely — the rock moves further. The third recalls a laborer who left without collecting his wage; he invested it honestly until it became whole herds of livestock, and when the man returned years later he gave him all of it — and the rock rolls away, freeing them.

From the hadith the speaker draws several lessons. First, the power of a sincere deed done in secret, and the permissibility of mentioning one's good deeds to Allah in dua — not as bargaining, but as part of the loving relationship Allah invites us into. Second, the enormous weight of goodness to parents: he answers the natural objection about the man feeding his parents before his children, explaining the man's lifelong habit and that his children were not neglected, and expands into a detailed teaching on birr al-walidayn — that we may disagree with parents but never with disrespect, that a mother is owed threefold care for carrying, birthing, and nursing us, and that even difficult parents retain rights, with the narrow exception of genuinely dangerous or abusive situations where a person should seek safety.

Third, he draws from the second man that turning away from a temptation one is able to indulge is itself a great act of worship — while warning against deliberately engineering temptations to "pass" them, which is a trap of Shaytan. Fourth, from the third man, he teaches honesty in wealth and trade: believers keep their contracts, and lying, concealing faults, or deceiving buyers destroys the blessing in one's wealth. Woven throughout is the theme of companionship — the three were saved together because they were righteous friends who reminded one another of Allah, and the Prophet ﷺ likened good and bad company to a perfume seller and a blacksmith's furnace. The lecture closes on the etiquette of dua — persistence with patience and contentment, not transgressing in what we ask — and a reflection on collective suffering, reminding listeners that Allah responds to every individual, that victory has many conditions beyond dua alone, and that we will be asked not why we did not change the world, but why we did not change ourselves.`,
